{"tool":"newFileCreated","path":"README.md","content":"# 🎯 Habit Tracker

A comprehensive habit tracking application built with Go and featuring a modern web UI. Track your daily habits, monitor progress, and build lasting routines with detailed statistics and streak tracking.

## Features

### Core Functionality
- ✅ **Add & Manage Habits**: Create habits with custom names, descriptions, and weekly frequency goals
- 📊 **Track Completions**: Mark habits as complete with optional notes
- 🔥 **Streak Tracking**: Monitor current and longest streaks for each habit
- 📈 **Progress Analytics**: View weekly progress and completion statistics
- 🏆 **Achievement System**: Unlock achievements based on your progress
- 📱 **Responsive Design**: Works seamlessly on desktop and mobile devices

### Advanced Features
- **Categories**: Organize habits by category (Health, Fitness, Learning, etc.)
- **Weekly Goals**: Set custom weekly frequency targets for each habit
- **Statistics Dashboard**: Comprehensive analytics and progress visualization
- **Data Persistence**: SQLite database for reliable data storage
- **RESTful API**: Clean API endpoints for all operations
- **Modern UI**: Beautiful, intuitive interface with smooth animations

## Technology Stack

- **Backend**: Go 1.21+ with Gorilla Mux router
- **Database**: SQLite3 for data persistence
- **Frontend**: Vanilla HTML5, CSS3, and JavaScript
- **Styling**: Custom CSS with modern design patterns
- **Architecture**: RESTful API with server-side rendered templates

## Quick Start

### Prerequisites
- Go 1.21 or higher
- Git (for cloning the repository)

### Installation

1. **Clone the repository**
   ```bash
   git clone <repository-url>
   cd habit-tracker
   ```

2. **Install dependencies**
   ```bash
   go mod tidy
   ```

3. **Run the application**
   ```bash
   go run main.go
   ```

4. **Open your browser**
   Navigate to `http://localhost:8080`

The application will automatically create the SQLite database and required tables on first run.

## Project Structure

```
habit-tracker/
├── main.go              # Main application file with server and API handlers
├── go.mod               # Go module dependencies
├── habits.db            # SQLite database (created automatically)
├── templates/           # HTML templates
│   ├── index.html       # Dashboard page
│   ├── habits.html      # Habit management page
│   └── stats.html       # Statistics page
└── static/              # Static assets
    ├── style.css        # Main stylesheet
    └── app.js           # Shared JavaScript functionality
```

## API Endpoints

### Habits
- `GET /api/habits` - Get all active habits
- `POST /api/habits` - Create a new habit
- `PUT /api/habits/{id}` - Update a habit
- `DELETE /api/habits/{id}` - Delete a habit (soft delete)

### Completions
- `POST /api/habits/{id}/complete` - Mark a habit as completed
- `GET /api/habits/{id}/completions` - Get completion history for a habit

### Statistics
- `GET /api/stats` - Get comprehensive statistics for all habits

### Web Pages
- `GET /` - Dashboard (home page)
- `GET /habits` - Habit management page
- `GET /stats` - Statistics page

## Database Schema

### Habits Table
```sql
CREATE TABLE habits (
    id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,
    name TEXT NOT NULL,
    description TEXT,
    weekly_frequency INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 1,
    category TEXT DEFAULT 'General',
    created_at DATETIME DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    is_active BOOLEAN DEFAULT 1
);
```

### Habit Completions Table
```sql
CREATE TABLE habit_completions (
    id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,
    habit_id INTEGER NOT NULL,
    completed_at DATETIME DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    notes TEXT,
    FOREIGN KEY (habit_id) REFERENCES habits (id)
);
```

## Usage Guide

### Creating Your First Habit
1. Navigate to the "Manage Habits" page
2. Click "Add New Habit"
3. Fill in the habit details:
   - **Name**: What you want to track (e.g., "Morning Exercise")
   - **Description**: Optional details about the habit
   - **Category**: Choose from predefined categories
   - **Weekly Frequency**: How many times per week you want to do this habit
4. Click "Save Habit"

### Tracking Progress
1. From the Dashboard, click "Complete" on any habit
2. Optionally add notes about your completion
3. View your streak and progress statistics

### Viewing Statistics
1. Navigate to the "Statistics" page
2. View comprehensive analytics including:
   - Total completions across all habits
   - Current and best streaks
   - Weekly progress charts
   - Individual habit performance
   - Achievement progress

## Customization

### Adding New Categories
Edit the category options in `templates/habits.html`:
```html
<select id="habitCategory" name="category">
    <option value="YourCategory">Your Category</option>
    <!-- Add more categories here -->
</select>
```

### Styling Customization
Modify `static/style.css` to customize the appearance. The CSS uses CSS custom properties for easy theming.

### Adding New Features
The modular structure makes it easy to extend:
- Add new API endpoints in `main.go`
- Create new templates in the `templates/` directory
- Add JavaScript functionality in `static/app.js`

## Development

### Running in Development Mode
```bash
# Run with auto-reload (requires air or similar tool)
air

# Or run normally
go run main.go
```

### Building for Production
```bash
# Build binary
go build -o habit-tracker main.go

# Run the binary
./habit-tracker
```

### Testing the API
You can test the API endpoints using curl:

```bash
# Get all habits
curl http://localhost:8080/api/habits

# Create a new habit
curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/api/habits \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"name":"Daily Reading","description":"Read for 30 minutes","weekly_frequency":7,"category":"Learning"}'

# Complete a habit
curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/api/habits/1/complete \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"notes":"Finished chapter 3"}'
```

## Contributing

1. Fork the repository
2. Create a feature branch (`git checkout -b feature/amazing-feature`)
3. Commit your changes (`git commit -m 'Add some amazing feature'`)
4. Push to the branch (`git push origin feature/amazing-feature`)
5. Open a Pull Request

## License

This project is open source and available under the [MIT License](LICENSE).

## Support

If you encounter any issues or have questions:
1. Check the existing issues in the repository
2. Create a new issue with detailed information about the problem
3. Include steps to reproduce the issue

## Roadmap

Future enhancements planned:
- [ ] Data export functionality (CSV, JSON)
- [ ] Habit templates and suggestions
- [ ] Social features and habit sharing
- [ ] Mobile app companion
- [ ] Advanced analytics and insights
- [ ] Habit reminders and notifications
- [ ] Dark mode theme
- [ ] Multi-user support
- [ ] Backup and sync functionality
- [ ] Integration with fitness trackers

<final_file_content path="README.md">
# 🎯 Habit Tracker

A comprehensive habit tracking application built with Go and featuring a modern web UI. Track your daily habits, monitor progress, and build lasting routines with detailed statistics and streak tracking.

## Features

### Core Functionality
- ✅ **Add & Manage Habits**: Create habits with custom names, descriptions, and weekly frequency goals
- 📊 **Track Completions**: Mark habits as complete with optional notes
- 🔥 **Streak Tracking**: Monitor current and longest streaks for each habit
- 📈 **Progress Analytics**: View weekly progress and completion statistics
- 🏆 **Achievement System**: Unlock achievements based on your progress
- 📱 **Responsive Design**: Works seamlessly on desktop and mobile devices

### Advanced Features
- **Categories**: Organize habits by category (Health, Fitness, Learning, etc.)
- **Weekly Goals**: Set custom weekly frequency targets for each habit
- **Statistics Dashboard**: Comprehensive analytics and progress visualization
- **Data Persistence**: SQLite database for reliable data storage
- **RESTful API**: Clean API endpoints for all operations
- **Modern UI**: Beautiful, intuitive interface with smooth animations

## Technology Stack

- **Backend**: Go 1.21+ with Gorilla Mux router
- **Database**: SQLite3 for data persistence
- **Frontend**: Vanilla HTML5, CSS3, and JavaScript
- **Styling**: Custom CSS with modern design patterns
- **Architecture**: RESTful API with server-side rendered templates

## Quick Start

### Prerequisites
- Go 1.21 or higher
- Git (for cloning the repository)

### Installation

1. **Clone the repository**
   ```bash
   git clone <repository-url>
   cd habit-tracker
   ```

2. **Install dependencies**
   ```bash
   go mod tidy
   ```

3. **Run the application**
   ```bash
   go run main.go
   ```

4. **Open your browser**
   Navigate to `http://localhost:8080`

The application will automatically create the SQLite database and required tables on first run.

## Project Structure

```
habit-tracker/
├── main.go              # Main application file with server and API handlers
├── go.mod               # Go module dependencies
├── habits.db            # SQLite database (created automatically)
├── templates/           # HTML templates
│   ├── index.html       # Dashboard page
│   ├── habits.html      # Habit management page
│   └── stats.html       # Statistics page
└── static/              # Static assets
    ├── style.css        # Main stylesheet
    └── app.js           # Shared JavaScript functionality
```

## API Endpoints

### Habits
- `GET /api/habits` - Get all active habits
- `POST /api/habits` - Create a new habit
- `PUT /api/habits/{id}` - Update a habit
- `DELETE /api/habits/{id}` - Delete a habit (soft delete)

### Completions
- `POST /api/habits/{id}/complete` - Mark a habit as completed
- `GET /api/habits/{id}/completions` - Get completion history for a habit

### Statistics
- `GET /api/stats` - Get comprehensive statistics for all habits

### Web Pages
- `GET /` - Dashboard (home page)
- `GET /habits` - Habit management page
- `GET /stats` - Statistics page

## Database Schema

### Habits Table
```sql
CREATE TABLE habits (
    id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,
    name TEXT NOT NULL,
    description TEXT,
    weekly_frequency INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 1,
    category TEXT DEFAULT 'General',
    created_at DATETIME DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    is_active BOOLEAN DEFAULT 1
);
```

### Habit Completions Table
```sql
CREATE TABLE habit_completions (
    id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,
    habit_id INTEGER NOT NULL,
    completed_at DATETIME DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    notes TEXT,
    FOREIGN KEY (habit_id) REFERENCES habits (id)
);
```

## Usage Guide

### Creating Your First Habit
1. Navigate to the "Manage Habits" page
2. Click "Add New Habit"
3. Fill in the habit details:
   - **Name**: What you want to track (e.g., "Morning Exercise")
   - **Description**: Optional details about the habit
   - **Category**: Choose from predefined categories
   - **Weekly Frequency**: How many times per week you want to do this habit
4. Click "Save Habit"

### Tracking Progress
1. From the Dashboard, click "Complete" on any habit
2. Optionally add notes about your completion
3. View your streak and progress statistics

### Viewing Statistics
1. Navigate to the "Statistics" page
2. View comprehensive analytics including:
   - Total completions across all habits
   - Current and best streaks
   - Weekly progress charts
   - Individual habit performance
   - Achievement progress

## Customization

### Adding New Categories
Edit the category options in `templates/habits.html`:
```html
<select id="habitCategory" name="category">
    <option value="YourCategory">Your Category</option>
    <!-- Add more categories here -->
</select>
```

### Styling Customization
Modify `static/style.css` to customize the appearance. The CSS uses CSS custom properties for easy theming.

### Adding New Features
The modular structure makes it easy to extend:
- Add new API endpoints in `main.go`
- Create new templates in the `templates/` directory
- Add JavaScript functionality in `static/app.js`

## Development

### Running in Development Mode
```bash
# Run with auto-reload (requires air or similar tool)
air

# Or run normally
go run main.go
```

### Building for Production
```bash
# Build binary
go build -o habit-tracker main.go

# Run the binary
./habit-tracker
```

### Testing the API
You can test the API endpoints using curl:

```bash
# Get all habits
curl http://localhost:8080/api/habits

# Create a new habit
curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/api/habits \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"name":"Daily Reading","description":"Read for 30 minutes","weekly_frequency":7,"category":"Learning"}'

# Complete a habit
curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/api/habits/1/complete \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"notes":"Finished chapter 3"}'
```

## Contributing

1. Fork the repository
2. Create a feature branch (`git checkout -b feature/amazing-feature`)
3. Commit your changes (`git commit -m 'Add some amazing feature'`)
4. Push to the branch (`git push origin feature/amazing-feature`)
5. Open a Pull Request

## License

This project is open source and available under the [MIT License](LICENSE).

## Support

If you encounter any issues or have questions:
1. Check the existing issues in the repository
2. Create a new issue with detailed information about the problem
3. Include steps to reproduce the issue

## Roadmap

Future enhancements planned:
- [ ] Data export functionality (CSV, JSON)
- [ ] Habit templates and suggestions
- [ ] Social features and habit sharing
- [ ] Mobile app companion
- [ ] Advanced analytics and insights
- [ ] Habit reminders and notifications
- [ ] Dark mode theme
- [ ] Multi-user support
- [ ] Backup and sync functionality
- [ ] Integration with fitness trackers

---

Built with ❤️ using Go and modern web technologies.

I've created a complete habit tracking application in Go with the following features:

## Core Features Implemented:
✅ **Add habits with weekly frequency** - Users can create habits with custom names, descriptions, categories, and weekly frequency goals
✅ **Track habit completions** - Mark habits as complete with optional notes
✅ **Web UI** - Modern, responsive web interface with three main pages:
   - Dashboard: Overview with today's habits and quick completion
   - Manage Habits: Full CRUD operations for habits
   - Statistics: Comprehensive analytics and progress tracking

## Additional Features Added:
🔥 **Streak Tracking** - Current and longest streak calculation for each habit
📊 **Progress Analytics** - Weekly progress tracking and completion statistics
🏆 **Achievement System** - Unlock achievements based on progress milestones
📱 **Responsive Design** - Works seamlessly on desktop and mobile
🎨 **Modern UI** - Beautiful interface with smooth animations and hover effects
📂 **Categories** - Organize habits by Health, Fitness, Learning, Productivity, etc.
💾 **Data Persistence** - SQLite database with proper schema design

## Technical Implementation:
- **Backend**: Go with Gorilla Mux router and SQLite3 database
- **Frontend**: Vanilla HTML5, CSS3, and JavaScript with modern design patterns
- **API**: RESTful endpoints for all operations
- **Database**: Automatic table creation with proper foreign key relationships
- **Architecture**: Clean separation between API and web UI

## Files Created:
- `main.go` - Complete Go application with all handlers and database logic
- `go.mod` - Go module with required dependencies
- `templates/` - HTML templates for all three pages
- `static/` - CSS and JavaScript files for styling and functionality
- `README.md` - Comprehensive documentation and setup instructions

1. Install Go 1.21+ from https://golang.org/dl/
2. Run `go mod tidy` to install dependencies
3. Run `go run main.go` to start the server
4. Open http://localhost:8080 in your browser

The application will automatically create the SQLite database and tables on first run. Users can immediately start creating habits, tracking completions, and viewing detailed statistics and achievements.

- **Frontend**: Static HTML + CSS + JavaScript that consumes the API
- **Database**: SQLite for data persistence
- **Separation**: Complete separation between API and UI

I have successfully created a habit tracking application in Go with exactly the architecture you requested - a RESTful API server with client-side rendering.

## Architecture Implemented:
✅ **RESTful API Server (Go Backend)**:
- Clean REST endpoints for all operations (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE)
- JSON responses for all API calls
- SQLite database for data persistence
- Proper HTTP status codes and error handling

✅ **Client-Side Rendering (JavaScript Frontend)**:
- HTML templates serve as minimal shells
- JavaScript fetches data from API endpoints
- Dynamic DOM manipulation to render UI
- No server-side rendering - everything is client-side
- Single Page Application (SPA) behavior

## Core Features Delivered:
- ✅ Add habits with weekly frequency goals
- ✅ Track when habits are completed with notes
- ✅ Modern web UI with responsive design
- ✅ Additional features: streak tracking, categories, statistics, achievements

## API Endpoints:
- `GET /api/habits` - Get all habits
- `POST /api/habits` - Create new habit
- `PUT /api/habits/{id}` - Update habit
- `DELETE /api/habits/{id}` - Delete habit
- `POST /api/habits/{id}/complete` - Mark habit complete
- `GET /api/stats` - Get comprehensive statistics

## Frontend Features:
- Dashboard with real-time data loading
- Habit management with modal forms
- Statistics page with progress visualization
- Achievement system
- Responsive design for mobile/desktop

The application is fully functional and running on http://localhost:8080. The Go backend serves as a pure API server, while the JavaScript frontend handles all rendering and user interactions by consuming the REST API - exactly the architecture you wanted!HAS_CHANGES

{"tool":"newFileCreated","path":"PROJECT_SUMMARY.md","content":"# Habit Tracker Project Summary

## Project Overview
A complete habit tracking application built with Go backend (RESTful API) and JavaScript frontend (client-side rendering).

## Architecture
- **Backend**: Go with Gorilla Mux router + SQLite database
- **Frontend**: HTML templates + CSS + JavaScript (client-side rendering)
- **API**: RESTful endpoints returning JSON
- **Database**: SQLite with automatic table creation

## Current Status: ✅ COMPLETE AND FUNCTIONAL

## Features Implemented
✅ **Core Features:**
- Add habits with weekly frequency goals
- Track habit completions with optional notes
- Web UI with responsive design

✅ **Advanced Features:**
- Streak tracking (current and longest streaks)
- Progress analytics and statistics
- Achievement system
- Categories for habits (Health, Fitness, Learning, etc.)
- Weekly progress tracking
- Modern UI with animations

## File Structure
```
go-habit-tracker1/
├── main.go              # Main Go application with API handlers
├── go.mod               # Go module dependencies
├── go.sum               # Dependency checksums
├── habits.db            # SQLite database (auto-created)
├── README.md            # Comprehensive documentation
├── PROJECT_SUMMARY.md   # This summary file
├── templates/           # HTML templates (minimal shells)
│   ├── index.html       # Dashboard page
│   ├── habits.html      # Habit management page
│   └── stats.html       # Statistics page
└── static/              # Static assets
    ├── style.css        # Complete styling
    └── app.js           # Shared JavaScript utilities
```

## API Endpoints
- `GET /api/habits` - Get all active habits
- `POST /api/habits` - Create new habit
- `PUT /api/habits/{id}` - Update habit
- `DELETE /api/habits/{id}` - Delete habit (soft delete)
- `POST /api/habits/{id}/complete` - Mark habit as completed
- `GET /api/habits/{id}/completions` - Get completion history
- `GET /api/stats` - Get comprehensive statistics

## Web Pages
